WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.542 --> 00:00:03.336
The success of our VQE algorithm heavily

2
00:00:03.336 --> 00:00:06.464
depends on the state and circuit
we choose to begin with.

3
00:00:06.881 --> 00:00:10.802
I'm Victoria Lipinska and in this video
we'll explore the options

4
00:00:10.802 --> 00:00:11.845
we have in designing them.

5
00:00:11.845 --> 00:00:15.473
Let's take a closer
look at all the elements

6
00:00:15.473 --> 00:00:18.643
we have in every run of the quantum
part of the VQE.

7
00:00:19.394 --> 00:00:23.189
We begin with the reference state,
sometimes called initial state.

8
00:00:23.481 --> 00:00:27.193
We run the reference state
through a parameterized circuit called

9
00:00:27.235 --> 00:00:30.697
a variational form
with an initial choice of parameters,

10
00:00:31.281 --> 00:00:34.743
and we measure the state
in the basis of the Hamiltonian

11
00:00:34.993 --> 00:00:40.165
after running it through the circuit
to obtain the expectation value. Now

12
00:00:40.165 --> 00:00:44.210
we'll walk through each of these elements,
starting with the reference state.

13
00:00:44.836 --> 00:00:48.298
A typical choice for the reference
state is the zero state.

14
00:00:48.465 --> 00:00:52.969
That is the state in which a quantum
computer is already initialized.

15
00:00:52.969 --> 00:00:55.346
For quantum chemistry problems,

16
00:00:55.346 --> 00:00:59.017
one can also use the so-called
Hartree-Fock State,

17
00:00:59.017 --> 00:01:01.770
which is the result of a Hartree-Fock
method.

18
00:01:02.437 --> 00:01:06.607
In a nutshell, Hartree-Fock
theory gives a simple way to construct

19
00:01:06.608 --> 00:01:10.987
the reference state by approximating
the ground state of a quantum system.

20
00:01:11.654 --> 00:01:14.532
It finds a rotation
within the space of states

21
00:01:14.783 --> 00:01:16.993
that minimizes the ground state energy.

22
00:01:17.535 --> 00:01:22.415
Finally, the reference state
can also be very problem specific,

23
00:01:22.624 --> 00:01:25.543
and you may want to choose
a custom state.

24
00:01:25.543 --> 00:01:30.172
In the case when you know what properties
your system has, for example, symmetries

25
00:01:30.173 --> 00:01:34.177
or a specific number of electrons
in the state, you can use that

26
00:01:34.427 --> 00:01:38.515
to have better convergence of the VQE
algorithm.

27
00:01:38.515 --> 00:01:42.310
Choosing a good reference
state is important for convergence

28
00:01:42.644 --> 00:01:45.271
reference states that are close to
the ground state

29
00:01:45.438 --> 00:01:48.733
can make the problem converge
much easier and faster.

30
00:01:49.275 --> 00:01:53.530
Similarly important
is the choice of initial parameter values

31
00:01:53.738 --> 00:01:56.407
that we feed into the variational form.

32
00:01:57.075 --> 00:02:00.703
Therefore, depending on the reference
state and initial parameters,

33
00:02:00.912 --> 00:02:04.874
we may converge quickly, slowly
or not converge at all.

34
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:08.919
Let's look at this plot
and for visualization purposes,

35
00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:13.925
let's imagine that our space of parameters
has only one parameter.

36
00:02:14.634 --> 00:02:18.304
A very good reference state
can allow you to start very close

37
00:02:18.304 --> 00:02:22.058
to the final ground state
and then convergence will be fast.

38
00:02:22.725 --> 00:02:26.688
On the other hand, if you start very far
from the ground state here,

39
00:02:26.688 --> 00:02:30.733
reference state
a, you will have to cross a high energy

40
00:02:30.733 --> 00:02:35.530
barrier leading to a very slow convergence
or no convergence at all.

41
00:02:35.947 --> 00:02:39.576
We will discuss this in more depth
in the classical optimization module

42
00:02:39.576 --> 00:02:40.952
in this course.

43
00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:45.582
Let's now look at the parameter circuit
that acts on the reference state, a.k.a.

44
00:02:45.748 --> 00:02:47.667
the variational form.

45
00:02:47.667 --> 00:02:50.962
When this circuit, the know,
the U of theta acts on the reference

46
00:02:50.962 --> 00:02:54.048
state,
it produces what we call a trial state

47
00:02:54.215 --> 00:02:57.718
psi of theta or sometimes ansatz.

48
00:02:57.719 --> 00:03:02.056
It is this ansatz state that is
then measured in an appropriate basis

49
00:03:02.307 --> 00:03:05.310
to obtain expectation
value for the energy.

50
00:03:05.935 --> 00:03:08.396
The variational forms
that we're discussing here

